Using the `equals` method avoids this problem by checking the content of each string object without reference equality issues. Here's an example:

```java
String str1 = "hello";
String str2 = "world";
String str3 = "hello";
String str4 = new String("hello");

// Comparing using == operator causes unexpected results
if (str1 == str3) { // true because they point to the same object
    System.out.println("They're the same!");
}
if (str1 == str4) { // false because they point to different objects
    System.out.println("They're the same! ");
}

// Comparing using equals method provides correct comparison results
if (str1.equals(str3)) { // true since "hello" is the same regardless of object identity
    System.out.println("Str1 and Str3 are equal.");
} else {
    System.out.println("Str1 and Str3 are unequal.");
}

if (str1.equals(str4)) { // false because even though "hello" is the same, these objects are not identical
    System.out.println("Str1 and Str4 are equal.");
} else {
    System.out.println("Str1 and Str4 are unequal.");
}

if (str1.equals(str2)) { // false since "hello" and "world" have different content
    System.out.println("Str1 and Str2 are equal.");
} else {
    System.out.println("Str1 and Str2 are unequal.");
}
```

Regarding when to use `==` versus `equals`, you should always utilize the `equals` method over string literals and user inputted variables due to potential null values, variable scope, and class type differences. Additionally, using the `equalsIgnoreCase` method allows users to ignore cases while performing comparative operations on strings, such as validating passwords entered with varying capitalization levels.

To summarize, utilizing the `equals` method, avoiding `==` usage, and accounting for scenario nuances help ensure accurate string comparability within your Java projects.

